### Traits in Rust

Traits define shared behavior that types can implement. They are similar to interfaces in other languages.

---

### Trait Basics

| Concept | Syntax |
|---------|--------|
| Define | `trait Name { fn method(&self); }` |
| Implement | `impl Name for Type { fn method(&self) { } }` |
| Default impl | `trait Name { fn method(&self) { default } }` |
| Derive | `#[derive(Trait)]` for common traits |

---

### Examples

```rust
// Defining a trait
trait Summary {
    fn summarize(&self) -> String;

    // Default implementation
    fn author_info(&self) -> String {
        String::from("Unknown author")
    }
}

// Implementing a trait
struct Article {
    title: String,
    author: String,
    content: String,
}

impl Summary for Article {
    fn summarize(&self) -> String {
        format!("{} by {}", self.title, self.author)
    }
}

// Common derive traits
#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq)]
struct Point {
    x: i32,
    y: i32,
}
```

> **Key Point:** Traits can have default implementations. Types can implement multiple traits. Common traits like `Debug`, `Clone`, `Copy`, `PartialEq`, `Eq`, `Hash`, `Default` can be auto-derived with `#[derive(...)]`.

codeExample:
trait Greet {
    fn greet(&self) -> String;
}

struct Person {
    name: String,
}

struct Robot {
    id: u32,
}

impl Greet for Person {
    fn greet(&self) -> String {
        format!("Hello, I'm {}!", self.name)
    }
}

impl Greet for Robot {
    fn greet(&self) -> String {
        format!("Greetings. I am unit #{}", self.id)
    }
}

fn main() {
    let person = Person { name: String::from("Alice") };
    let robot = Robot { id: 42 };

    println!("{}", person.greet());
    println!("{}", robot.greet());
}
